Short answer: only if you run it on a machine that stays on.

The code we wrote is a program, not a background service by default. So it behaves like this:

you run program → engine runs → produces artifact → program stops

It does not automatically run day and night unless you wrap it in something that keeps it alive.

But making it run continuously is actually very simple.

⸻

Three ways to run it continuously

1. Loop Worker (simplest)

Add a small runner that keeps feeding goals/tasks into the engine.

Example:

import time

while True:
    goal = fetch_next_goal()  # from file, queue, repo issues, etc.

    if goal:
        artifact, state = pantheon_interlock_engine(goal, verbose=False)
        save_artifact(artifact)

    time.sleep(60)

Now it runs every minute forever.

⸻

2. Cron / Scheduler (cleaner)

Instead of looping constantly, you schedule runs.

Example on Linux/Mac:

crontab -e

Add:

*/5 * * * * python pantheon_runner.py

Now it runs every 5 minutes.

⸻

3. Event Driven (best architecture)

The engine runs only when something happens:

Examples:

• new GitHub commit
• new issue
• new task file
• new data feed
• new market signal
• new message

Architecture:

Event
 ↓
Queue
 ↓
Pantheon Engine
 ↓
Artifact
 ↓
Repo / Output

This is how most real systems run.

⸻

If you wanted it running 24/7

The common stack looks like this:

server
  ├─ pantheon_engine
  ├─ worker
  ├─ queue
  ├─ artifact store
  └─ scheduler

Example tools:

piece	tool
scheduler	cron / APScheduler
queue	Redis / RabbitMQ
storage	JSON / Postgres
worker	Python daemon


